\section{\texorpdfstring{Introduction\hyperref[introduction]{}}{Introduction}}\label{introduction}

\href{https://github.com/mpark/wg21}{\VERB|\NormalTok{MPark}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{WG21}|}
is a framework for writing proposals for the C++ Standards Committee,
built on top of \href{https://pandoc.org}{Pandoc}.

In short, you write \textbf{Markdown} and the framework produces the
paper either in \textbf{HTML} or \textbf{PDF} (via LaTeX).

The framework provides Markdown extensions that are specifically useful
for C++ proposals. Including, but not limited to:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \hyperref[modifying-text]{Modifying Wording Text}
\item
  \hyperref[embedded-markdown]{Embedded Markdown in Code}
\end{itemize}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Goals\hyperref[goals]{}}{Goals}}\label{goals}

There are two goals for this framework, not necessarily in order:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Ease of \textbf{authoring} papers
\item
  Ease of \textbf{reviewing} papers
\end{itemize}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Getting
Started\hyperref[getting-started]{}}{Getting Started}}\label{getting-started}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Requirements\hyperref[requirements]{}}{Requirements}}\label{requirements}

The framework downloads and maintains a pinned version of Pandoc.

For HTML output, only the following dependencies are required:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{git}|
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{curl}|
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{make}|
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{python3}|
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{python3}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{venv}|
\end{itemize}

For PDF output, the framework also depends on
\VERB|\NormalTok{xelatex}|.

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{macOS\hyperref[macos]{}}{macOS}}\label{macos}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ExtensionTok{brew}\NormalTok{ install python make}

\CommentTok{\# For PDF output}
\ExtensionTok{brew}\NormalTok{ install }\AttributeTok{{-}{-}cask}\NormalTok{ mactex}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Ubuntu\hyperref[ubuntu]{}}{Ubuntu}}\label{ubuntu}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{sudo}\NormalTok{ apt{-}get install git curl make python3 python3{-}venv}

\CommentTok{\# For PDF output}
\FunctionTok{sudo}\NormalTok{ apt{-}get install texlive{-}xetex}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Debian\hyperref[debian]{}}{Debian}}\label{debian}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{sudo}\NormalTok{ apt{-}get install git curl make python3 python3{-}venv}

\CommentTok{\# For PDF output}
\FunctionTok{sudo}\NormalTok{ apt{-}get install texlive{-}xetex }\DataTypeTok{\textbackslash{}}
\NormalTok{                     texlive{-}fonts{-}recommended }\DataTypeTok{\textbackslash{}}
\NormalTok{                     texlive{-}latex{-}recommended }\DataTypeTok{\textbackslash{}}
\NormalTok{                     texlive{-}latex{-}extra}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Integration\hyperref[integration]{}}{Integration}}\label{integration}

Add this repository to your paper repository as a git submodule:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{git}\NormalTok{ submodule add https://github.com/mpark/wg21.git}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Then include the framework \VERB|\NormalTok{Makefile}| from your
repository's top-level \VERB|\NormalTok{Makefile}|:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{include wg21/Makefile}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Markdown files in the repository root become build targets. For example,
\VERB|\NormalTok{P0000R0}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{md}| can be built as
\VERB|\NormalTok{generated}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{P0000R0}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{html}|
or
\VERB|\NormalTok{generated}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{P0000R0}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{pdf}|.

See \href{https://github.com/mpark/wg21-papers}{mpark/wg21-papers} for
an example use of this project.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Generation\hyperref[generation]{}}{Generation}}\label{generation}

Given a \VERB|\NormalTok{P0000R0}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{md}| at the
top-level of your repository:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{make}\NormalTok{ generated/P0000R0.html  }\CommentTok{\# HTML Output}
\FunctionTok{make}\NormalTok{ generated/P0000R0.pdf   }\CommentTok{\# PDF Output}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

For convenience, the \VERB|\NormalTok{Makefile}| also accepts:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{make}\NormalTok{ P0000R0.html  }\CommentTok{\# HTML Output}
\FunctionTok{make}\NormalTok{ P0000R0.pdf   }\CommentTok{\# PDF Output}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

In both cases, the output is written under
\VERB|\NormalTok{generated}\OperatorTok{/}|.

\section{\texorpdfstring{Formatting\hyperref[formatting]{}}{Formatting}}\label{formatting}

This framework provides support for various common elements for C++
proposals.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Title\hyperref[title]{}}{Title}}\label{title}

The title is specified in a
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-yaml_metadata_block}{YAML
metadata block}.

For example, the \hyperref[title-block-header]{title} of this document
is generated from:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

{{{[} \emph{Note:}
}\VERB|\NormalTok{date}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{ today}| generates
today's date in
\VERB|\NormalTok{YYYY}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{MM}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{DD}|
(ISO 8601) format.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

YAML lists can be used to specify multiple audiences and authors:

{

\renewcommand{\NormalTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{898887}{#1}}

\renewcommand{\VariableTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{006e28}{#1}}

\renewcommand{\StringTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{bf0303}{#1}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{  {-}{-}{-}}
\NormalTok{  title: "\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\NormalTok{  subtitle: "Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\NormalTok{  document: D0000R0}
\NormalTok{  date: today}
\StringTok{{-} audience: WG21}
\VariableTok{+ audience:}
\VariableTok{+   {-} Library Evolution Working Group}
\VariableTok{+   {-} Library Working Group}
\NormalTok{  author:}
\NormalTok{    {-} name: Michael Park}
\NormalTok{      email: \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\VariableTok{+   {-} name: Barry Revzin}
\VariableTok{+     email: \textless{}barry.revzin@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\KeywordTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Table of
Contents\hyperref[table-of-contents]{}}{Table of Contents}}\label{table-of-contents}

By default, a table of contents is generated. For an example, see the
\hyperref[toctitle]{table of contents} of this document.

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Metadata:
\texttt{toc}\hyperref[metadata-toc]{}}{Metadata: toc}}\label{metadata-toc}

To disable the table of contents entirely, set the
\VERB|\NormalTok{toc}| metadata to \VERB|\KeywordTok{false}|.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{toc: false}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Metadata:
\texttt{toc-depth}\hyperref[metadata-toc-depth]{}}{Metadata: toc-depth}}\label{metadata-toc-depth}

The default depth of table of contents is \VERB|\DecValTok{3}|. That is,
given headers like

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\# Design Overview}

\NormalTok{\#\# Types of Patterns}

\NormalTok{\#\#\# Primary Patterns}

\NormalTok{\#\#\#\# Wildcard Pattern}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The table of contents will not show
\VERB|\NormalTok{\#\#\#\# Wildcard Pattern}| since it's 4 levels deep.

To set the depth manually, set
\VERB|\NormalTok{toc}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{depth}| to the desired
number.\\
For example, to make \VERB|\NormalTok{\#\#\#\# Wildcard Pattern}| show
up:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{toc-depth: 4}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Headings\hyperref[headings]{}}{Headings}}\label{headings}

Both Setext and ATX styles are available:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4167}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4167}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Header 1}
\NormalTok{========}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\section*{\texorpdfstring{Header
1\hyperref[header-1]{}}{Header 1}}\label{header-1}
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Header 2}
\NormalTok{{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{Header
2\hyperref[header-2]{}}{Header 2}}\label{header-2}
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#\#\# Header 3}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\subsubsection*{\texorpdfstring{Header
3\hyperref[header-3]{}}{Header 3}}\label{header-3}
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#\#\#\# Header 4}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\paragraph*{\texorpdfstring{Header
4\hyperref[header-4]{}}{Header 4}}\label{header-4}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Disable from Section Numbering:
\texttt{-} or
\texttt{.unnumbered}\hyperref[disable-section-number]{}}{Disable from Section Numbering: - or .unnumbered}}\label{disable-section-number}

Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}| or
\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{unnumbered}| class to a header to
exclude it from section numbering, using the Pandoc extension
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-header_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{header\_attributes}|}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{\# Miscelleneous \{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{-}}}\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Exclude from Table of Contents:
\texttt{.unlisted}\hyperref[exclude-from-toc]{}}{Exclude from Table of Contents: .unlisted}}\label{exclude-from-toc}

Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{unlisted}| class \textbf{in
addition to} \VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}| or
\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{unnumbered}| to a header to exclude it
from the table of contents, using the Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-header_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{header\_attributes}|}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{\# Miscelleneous \{{-} {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{.unlisted}}}\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Implicit Header
References\hyperref[implicit-header-references]{}}{Implicit Header References}}\label{implicit-header-references}

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Given a heading like:}

\NormalTok{\#\# Algorithm Return Type \{{-} .unlisted\}}

\NormalTok{Reference with any of the following ways:}

\NormalTok{  {-} [Algorithm Return Type]}
\NormalTok{  {-} [Algorithm Return Type][]}
\NormalTok{  {-} [Custom Text 1][Algorithm Return Type]}
\NormalTok{  {-} [Custom Text 2](\#algorithm{-}return{-}type)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Given a heading like:

\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{Algorithm Return
Type\hyperref[algorithm-return-type]{}}{Algorithm Return Type}}\label{algorithm-return-type}

Reference with any of the following ways:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \hyperref[algorithm-return-type]{Algorithm Return Type}
\item
  \hyperref[algorithm-return-type]{Algorithm Return Type}
\item
  \hyperref[algorithm-return-type]{Custom Text 1}
\item
  \hyperref[algorithm-return-type]{Custom Text 2}
\end{itemize}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

The \VERB|\NormalTok{\#algorithm{-}return{-}type}| identifier is
automatically generated by the Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-auto_identifiers}{\VERB|\NormalTok{auto\_identifiers}|}.

Relevant Pandoc extensions:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-implicit_header_references}{\VERB|\NormalTok{implicit\_header\_references}|},
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-shortcut_reference_links}{\VERB|\NormalTok{shortcut\_reference\_links}|}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Header References by ID with Automatic
Text\hyperref[header-references-by-id-with-automatic-text]{}}{Header References by ID with Automatic Text}}\label{header-references-by-id-with-automatic-text}

This extension interprets \VERB|\NormalTok{[](\#header{-}identifier)}|
as a reference to a header where the heading text is automatically used.

The main usage is to first specify an explicit identifier on a header,
like:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{\#\# Algorithm Return Type {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{\{\#return-type\}}}}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

then refer to it like \VERB|\NormalTok{[](\#return{-}type)}|, which will
be rendered as: Algorithm Return Type.

The main advantage is that when the header text changes, the reference
remains stable and the new heading text is automatically rendered.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Inline
Formatting\hyperref[inline-formatting]{}}{Inline Formatting}}\label{inline-formatting}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Emphasis\hyperref[emphasis]{}}{Emphasis}}\label{emphasis}

Use asterisks (\VERB|\OperatorTok{*}|) and underscores
(\VERB|\NormalTok{\_}|) to emphasize inline text.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5361}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4639}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{Some of these words *are emphasized*.}| & Some of these
words \emph{are emphasized}. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Some of these words \_are emphasized also\_.}| & Some
of these words \emph{are emphasized also}. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Use two asterisks for **strong emphasis**.}| & Use two
asterisks for \textbf{strong emphasis}. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Or, \_\_use two underscores instead\_\_.}| & Or,
\textbf{use two underscores instead}. \\
\end{longtable}
}

For emphasizing \textbf{part} of a word, asterisks are
\textbf{required}.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5479}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4521}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{feas**ible**, not feas\_\_able\_\_}| &
feas\textbf{ible}, not feas\_\_able\_\_ \\
\end{longtable}
}

This is the Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-intraword_underscores}{\VERB|\NormalTok{intraword\_underscores}|}.

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Superscript,
Subscript\hyperref[superscript-subscript]{}}{Superscript, Subscript}}\label{superscript-subscript}

Wrap caret (\VERB|\OperatorTok{\^{}}|) for superscripts and tilde
(\VERB|\OperatorTok{\textasciitilde{}}|) for subscripts.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5696}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4304}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{2\^{}10\^{} is 1024}| & 2\textsuperscript{10} is
1024 \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}constexpr\textasciigrave{}\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{} means optional}|
& \VERB|\KeywordTok{constexpr}|\textsubscript{opt} means optional \\
\end{longtable}
}

This is the Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-superscript-subscript}{\VERB|\NormalTok{superscript\_subscript}|}.

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Highlighting\hyperref[highlighting]{}}{Highlighting}}\label{highlighting}

Wrap \VERB|\OperatorTok{==}|, or use
\VERB|\NormalTok{[highlighted text]\{.mark\}}| to highlight some text.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5422}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4578}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{This is a ==highlighted **text**==.}| & This is a
{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{highlighted
\textbf{text}}}}. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Also, [highlight *text*]\{.mark\}}| & Also,
{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{highlight \emph{text}}}} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Wording\hyperref[wording]{}}{Wording}}\label{wording}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Modifying
Text\hyperref[modifying-text]{}}{Modifying Text}}\label{modifying-text}

Small, inline changes are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Span}| elements} that look like the following:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5347}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4653}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{Let\textquotesingle{}s add some [new **text**]\{.add\}.}|
& Let's add some {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{new \textbf{text}}}}. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Remove some [old *text*]\{.rm\} now.}| & Remove some
{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{old \emph{text}}}} now. \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{Substitute: [old *text*](new **text**)\{.sub\}}| &
Substitute: {{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{old
\emph{text}}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{new \textbf{text}}}}} \\
\end{longtable}
}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }Substitutions are essentially just shorthand for
\VERB|\NormalTok{[old text]\{.rm\}[new text]\{.add\}}|.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{The optional *attribute{-}specifier{-}seq* appertains to the [label](*general{-}label*)\{.sub\}.}
\NormalTok{The only use of a [label with an *identifier*](*label*)\{.sub\} is as the target of}
\NormalTok{a \textasciigrave{}goto\textasciigrave{}, [\textasciigrave{}break\textasciigrave{}, or \textasciigrave{}continue\textasciigrave{}]\{.add\}. No two [label](*label*)\{.sub\}s in a function}
\NormalTok{shall have the same *identifier*. A [label](*general{-}label*)\{.sub\} can be used}
\NormalTok{[in a \textasciigrave{}goto\textasciigrave{} statement]\{.rm\} before its introduction by a *labeled{-}statement*.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

The optional \emph{attribute-specifier-seq} appertains to the
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{general-label}}}}}.
The only use of a {{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label with an
\emph{identifier}}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{label}}}}} is as
the target of a \VERB|\ControlFlowTok{goto}|,
{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{break}|, or
\VERB|\NormalTok{continue}|}}}. No two
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{label}}}}}s
in a function shall have the same \emph{identifier}. A
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{general-label}}}}}
can be used {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{in a \VERB|\NormalTok{goto}|
statement}}} before its introduction by a \emph{labeled-statement}.
\end{quote}

Large changes are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{fenced
\VERB|\NormalTok{Div}| blocks} with \VERB|\NormalTok{::: add}| for
additions, \VERB|\NormalTok{::: rm}| for removals, and close with
\VERB|\NormalTok{:::}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Modify section [format.functions]\{.sref\}}

\NormalTok{::: add}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} \textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} template\textless{}class... Args\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}   string format(const locale\& loc, string\_view fmt, const Args\&... args);}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} \textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} *Returns*: \textasciigrave{}vformat(loc, fmt, make\_format\_args(args...))\textasciigrave{}.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

Modify section {28.5.5 Formatting functions
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/format.functions}{{[}format.functions{]}}}

{\color[HTML]{006e28}

\begin{quote}
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{template\textless{}class... Args\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{  string format(const locale\& loc, string\_view fmt, const Args\&... args);}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\emph{Returns}:
\VERB|\NormalTok{vformat(loc, fmt, make\_format\_args(args...))}|.
\end{quote}

}
\end{quote}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Remove [expr.post.incr]\{.sref\}/2:}

\NormalTok{::: rm}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} The operand of postfix \textasciigrave{}{-}{-}\textasciigrave{} is decremented analogously to the postfix \textasciigrave{}++\textasciigrave{} operator.}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} [For prefix increment and decrement, see [expr.pre.incr].]\{.note\} }
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

Remove {7.6.1.6 Increment and decrement
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/expr.post.incr\#2}{{[}expr.post.incr{]}/2}}:

{\color[HTML]{bf0303}

\begin{quote}
The operand of postfix \VERB|\NormalTok{{-}{-}}| is decremented
analogously to the postfix \VERB|\NormalTok{++}| operator.

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }For prefix increment and decrement, see
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/expr.pre.incr}{{[}expr.pre.incr{]}}.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}
\end{quote}

}
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Paragraph
Numbers\hyperref[paragraph-numbers]{}}{Paragraph Numbers}}\label{paragraph-numbers}

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{Paragraph Number Element:
\texttt{.pnum}\hyperref[paragraph-number-element-.pnum]{}}{Paragraph Number Element: .pnum}}\label{paragraph-number-element-.pnum}

Paragraph number elements are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Span}| elements} that look like:
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{pnum}\OperatorTok{\}}|
and
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\FloatTok{2.1}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{pnum}\OperatorTok{\}}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{[1]\{.pnum\} In this subclause, "before" and "after" refer to the "happens before"}
\NormalTok{relation ([intro.multithread]).}

\NormalTok{[2]\{.pnum\} The *lifetime* of an object or reference is a runtime property of}
\NormalTok{the object or reference. [...]}

\NormalTok{  {-} [2.1]\{.pnum\} storage with the proper alignment and size for type \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is obtained, and}

\NormalTok{    [...]}

\NormalTok{  {-} [2.4]\{.pnum\} if \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is a class type, the destructor call starts, or}
\NormalTok{  {-} [2.5]\{.pnum\} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is reused by}
\NormalTok{    an object that is not nested within \_o\_ ([intro.object]).}

\NormalTok{[...]}

\NormalTok{::: add}
\NormalTok{[x]\{.pnum\} Some new paragraph here}
\NormalTok{:::}

\NormalTok{[6]\{.pnum\} A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type without}
\NormalTok{invoking the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as described above.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\pnum{1} In this subclause, ``before'' and ``after'' refer to the
``happens before'' relation
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.multithread}{{[}intro.multithread{]}}).

\pnum{2} The \emph{lifetime} of an object or reference is a runtime
property of the object or reference. {[}\ldots{]}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} storage with the proper alignment and size for type
  \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is obtained, and

  {[}\ldots{]}
\item
  \pnum{(2.4)} if \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is a class type, the destructor
  call starts, or
\item
  \pnum{(2.5)} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is
  reused by an object that is not nested within \emph{o}
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.object}{{[}intro.object{]}}).
\end{itemize}

{[}\ldots{]}

{\color[HTML]{006e28}\pnum{x} Some new paragraph here}

\pnum{6} A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type
without invoking the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as
described above.
\end{quote}

Within \VERB|\NormalTok{::: wording}|, use \VERB|\NormalTok{\#}| within
a paragraph number element to automatically fill in that part. For
example:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: wording}
\NormalTok{[\#]\{.pnum\} Automatically starts at 1.}

\NormalTok{[5]\{.pnum\} Existing paragraph pinned at 5.}

\NormalTok{[\#]\{.pnum\} Automatically continues to 6.}

\NormalTok{[\#.\#]\{.pnum\} Automatically starts a nested numbering at (6.1).}

\NormalTok{::: add}
\NormalTok{[x]\{.pnum\} Added paragraph that does not affect the next automatic number.}
\NormalTok{:::}

\NormalTok{[\#]\{.pnum\} Automatically continues to 7.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\pnum{1} Automatically starts at 1.

\pnum{5} Existing paragraph pinned at 5.

\pnum{6} Automatically continues to 6.

\pnum{(6.1)} Automatically starts a nested numbering at (6.1).

{\color[HTML]{006e28}\pnum{x} Added paragraph that does not affect the
next automatic number.}

\pnum{7} Automatically continues to 7.
\end{quote}

The automatic numbering resets for each \VERB|\NormalTok{::: wording}|
div.

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{List-based Paragraphs
(Experimental)\hyperref[list-based-paragraphs-experimental]{}}{List-based Paragraphs (Experimental)}}\label{list-based-paragraphs-experimental}

List-based paragraphs are list elements
(\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#ordered-lists}{\VERB|\NormalTok{ordered\_lists}|}
and
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#bullet-lists}{\VERB|\NormalTok{bullet\_lists}|}),
within a \href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Div}| element}, \VERB|\NormalTok{::: wording}|.

At the top-level, use \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| for automatic numbering,
and \VERB|\FloatTok{1.}| for pinned numbering. For example:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: wording}
\NormalTok{\#. In this subclause, "before" and "after" refer to the "happens before" relation}
\NormalTok{   ([intro.multithread]).}
\NormalTok{\#. The *lifetime* of an object or reference is a runtime property of the object}
\NormalTok{   or reference. [...]}

\NormalTok{[...]}

\NormalTok{6. A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type without invoking}
\NormalTok{   the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as described above.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\pnum{1} In this subclause, ``before'' and ``after'' refer to the
``happens before'' relation
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.multithread}{{[}intro.multithread{]}}).

\pnum{2} The \emph{lifetime} of an object or reference is a runtime
property of the object or reference. {[}\ldots{]}

{[}\ldots{]}

\pnum{6} A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type
without invoking the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as
described above.
\end{quote}

Use nested bullet lists for sublists which are also automatically
numbered, and \VERB|\FloatTok{1.}| for partial pinning. For example, if
we pin \VERB|\FloatTok{3.}| within paragraph \VERB|\DecValTok{2}|,
partial pinning will work out to
\VERB|\OperatorTok{(}\FloatTok{2.3}\OperatorTok{)}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: wording}
\NormalTok{\#. In this subclause, "before" and "after" refer to the "happens before" relation}
\NormalTok{   ([intro.multithread]).}
\NormalTok{\#. The *lifetime* of an object or reference is a runtime property of the object}
\NormalTok{   or reference. [...]}

\NormalTok{   {-} storage with the proper alignment and size for type \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is obtained, and}

\NormalTok{     [...]}

\NormalTok{   4. if \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is a class type, the destructor call starts, or}
\NormalTok{   {-} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is reused by}
\NormalTok{     an object that is not nested within \_o\_ ([intro.object]).}

\NormalTok{[...]}

\NormalTok{6. A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type without invoking}
\NormalTok{   the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as described above.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\pnum{1} In this subclause, ``before'' and ``after'' refer to the
``happens before'' relation
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.multithread}{{[}intro.multithread{]}}).

\pnum{2} The \emph{lifetime} of an object or reference is a runtime
property of the object or reference. {[}\ldots{]}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} storage with the proper alignment and size for type
  \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is obtained, and

  {[}\ldots{]}
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.4)} if \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is a class type, the destructor
  call starts, or
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.5)} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is
  reused by an object that is not nested within \emph{o}
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.object}{{[}intro.object{]}}).
\end{itemize}

{[}\ldots{]}

\pnum{6} A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type
without invoking the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as
described above.
\end{quote}

Lastly, use \VERB|\NormalTok{x}\OperatorTok{.}| to mark a paragraph
number \VERB|\NormalTok{x}|. This is most useful within an
\VERB|\OperatorTok{:::}\NormalTok{ add}| block where you want to insert
new paragraphs without having to manually shift the numbers.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: wording}
\NormalTok{\#. In this subclause, "before" and "after" refer to the "happens before" relation}
\NormalTok{   ([intro.multithread]).}
\NormalTok{\#. The *lifetime* of an object or reference is a runtime property of the object}
\NormalTok{   or reference. [...]}

\NormalTok{   {-} storage with the proper alignment and size for type \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is obtained, and}

\NormalTok{     [...]}

\NormalTok{   4. if \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{} is a class type, the destructor call starts, or}
\NormalTok{   {-} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is reused by}
\NormalTok{     an object that is not nested within \_o\_ ([intro.object]).}

\NormalTok{[...]}

\NormalTok{::: add}
\NormalTok{x. Some new paragraph here}
\NormalTok{:::}

\NormalTok{6. A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type without invoking}
\NormalTok{   the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as described above.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\pnum{1} In this subclause, ``before'' and ``after'' refer to the
``happens before'' relation
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.multithread}{{[}intro.multithread{]}}).

\pnum{2} The \emph{lifetime} of an object or reference is a runtime
property of the object or reference. {[}\ldots{]}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} storage with the proper alignment and size for type
  \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is obtained, and

  {[}\ldots{]}
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.4)} if \VERB|\NormalTok{T}| is a class type, the destructor
  call starts, or
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.5)} the storage which the object occupies is released, or is
  reused by an object that is not nested within \emph{o}
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.object}{{[}intro.object{]}}).
\end{itemize}

{[}\ldots{]}

{\color[HTML]{006e28}\pnum{x} Some new paragraph here}

\pnum{6} A program may end the lifetime of an object of class type
without invoking the destructor, by reusing or releasing the storage as
described above.
\end{quote}

{{[} \emph{Note:} }In order to nest content (code blocks, nested list,
etc) properly within another list, be sure to add a blank line and
indent to line up with the first non-space character after the list
marker. See Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#block-content-in-list-items}{\VERB|\NormalTok{block\_content\_in\_list\_items}|}.

{{[} \emph{Example:} }

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4949}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5051}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Preceding blank line}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Indent to line up}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#. Some paragraph}
\NormalTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~}}}}
\NormalTok{   \textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{   code}
\NormalTok{   \textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#. {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{S}}}ome paragraph}
\NormalTok{   {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{~}}}}
\NormalTok{   {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{`}}}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{   {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{c}}}ode}
\NormalTok{   {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{`}}}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

{ --- \emph{end example} {]}}

For nested lists, the blank line may be omitted:

{{[} \emph{Example:} }

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#. {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{S}}}ome paragraph}
\NormalTok{   {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{-}}} Nested bullet list}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

{ --- \emph{end example} {]}}

{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Code
Changes\hyperref[code-changes]{}}{Code Changes}}\label{code-changes}

Code changes can be either shown in a \VERB|\NormalTok{diff}| code block
like so:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}diff}
\NormalTok{  template \textless{}size\_t I, class T1, class T2\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{{-}   constexpr typename tuple\_element\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}::type\&}
\NormalTok{+   constexpr tuple\_element\_t\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}\&}
\NormalTok{      get(pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\&) noexcept;}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{

\renewcommand{\NormalTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{898887}{#1}}

\renewcommand{\VariableTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{006e28}{#1}}

\renewcommand{\StringTok}[1]{\textcolor[HTML]{bf0303}{#1}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{  template \textless{}size\_t I, class T1, class T2\textgreater{}}
\StringTok{{-}   constexpr typename tuple\_element\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}::type\&}
\VariableTok{+   constexpr tuple\_element\_t\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}\&}
\NormalTok{      get(pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\&) noexcept;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

}
\end{quote}

Alternatively, \hyperref[embedded-markdown]{Embedded Markdown} can be
used to show the changes inline:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{template \textless{}size\_t I, class T1, class T2\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{  constexpr @[typename]\{.rm\}@ tuple\_element@[\_t]\{.add\}@\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}@[::type]\{.rm\}@\&}
\NormalTok{    get(pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\&) noexcept;}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{template \textless{}size\_t I, class T1, class T2\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{  constexpr {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{typename}}} tuple\_element{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\_t}}}\textless{}I, pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\textgreater{}{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{::type}}}\&}
\NormalTok{    get(pair\textless{}T1, T2\textgreater{}\&) noexcept;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{quote}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }For inline changes like this, prefer
no-syntax-highlighting by using
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}|
to avoid too many colors.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Examples\hyperref[examples]{}}{Examples}}\label{examples}

Smaller, inline examples are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Span}| elements} that looks like
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{example text}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{example}\OperatorTok{\}}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{[\textasciigrave{}T x = T(T(T()));\textasciigrave{} value{-}initializes \textasciigrave{}x\textasciigrave{}.]\{.example\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{{{[} \emph{Example:}
}\VERB|\NormalTok{T x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ T}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{T}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{T}\OperatorTok{()));}|
value-initializes \VERB|\NormalTok{x}|.{ --- \emph{end example} {]}}}
\end{quote}

Large examples are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{fenced
\VERB|\NormalTok{Div}| blocks} with
\VERB|\OperatorTok{:::}\NormalTok{ example}|.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: example}
\NormalTok{A simple example of a class definition is}

\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{struct tnode \{}
\NormalTok{  char tword[20];}
\NormalTok{  int count;}
\NormalTok{  tnode* left;}
\NormalTok{  tnode* right;}
\NormalTok{\};}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
{{[} \emph{Example:} }A simple example of a class definition is

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{struct}\NormalTok{ tnode }\OperatorTok{\{}
  \DataTypeTok{char}\NormalTok{ tword}\OperatorTok{[}\DecValTok{20}\OperatorTok{];}
  \DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ count}\OperatorTok{;}
\NormalTok{  tnode}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ left}\OperatorTok{;}
\NormalTok{  tnode}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ right}\OperatorTok{;}
\OperatorTok{\};}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

{ --- \emph{end example} {]}}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Notes\hyperref[notes]{}}{Notes}}\label{notes}

Smaller, inline notes are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Span}| elements} that looks like
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{note text}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{note}\OperatorTok{\}}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{[Padding bits have unspecified value, but cannot cause traps.]\{.note\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }Padding bits have unspecified value, but cannot
cause traps.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}
\end{quote}

Large notes are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{fenced
\VERB|\NormalTok{Div}| blocks} with
\VERB|\OperatorTok{:::}\NormalTok{ note}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: note}
\NormalTok{An expression of type "*cv1* \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{}" can initialize an object of type "*cv2* \textasciigrave{}T\textasciigrave{}"}
\NormalTok{independently of the cv{-}qualifiers *cv1* and *cv2*.}

\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{int a;}
\NormalTok{const int b = a;}
\NormalTok{int c = b;}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{{[} \emph{Note:} }An expression of type ``\emph{cv1}
\VERB|\NormalTok{T}|'' can initialize an object of type ``\emph{cv2}
\VERB|\NormalTok{T}|'' independently of the cv-qualifiers \emph{cv1} and
\emph{cv2}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ a}\OperatorTok{;}
\KeywordTok{const} \DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ b }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ a}\OperatorTok{;}
\DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ c }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ b}\OperatorTok{;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}
\end{quote}

Use \VERB|\NormalTok{ednote}| for editorial notes:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{[This is a drive{-}by fix.]\{.ednote\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
{{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Editor\textquotesingle s note: This is a
drive-by fix. {]}}}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: ednote}
\NormalTok{Throughout the wording, we say that a reflection (an object of type \textasciigrave{}std::meta::info\textasciigrave{})}
\NormalTok{represents some source construct, while splicing that reflection designates that source}
\NormalTok{construct. For instance, \textasciigrave{}\^{}\^{}int\textasciigrave{} represents the type \textasciigrave{}int\textasciigrave{} and \textasciigrave{}[: \^{}\^{}int :]\textasciigrave{} designates}
\NormalTok{the type \textasciigrave{}int\textasciigrave{}.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Editor\textquotesingle s note: Throughout the
wording, we say that a reflection (an object of type
\VERB|\NormalTok{std::meta::info}|) represents some source construct,
while splicing that reflection designates that source construct. For
instance, \VERB|\NormalTok{\^{}\^{}int}| represents the type
\VERB|\NormalTok{int}| and \VERB|\NormalTok{[: \^{}\^{}int :]}|
designates the type \VERB|\NormalTok{int}|. {]}}
\end{quote}

Use \VERB|\NormalTok{draftnote}| for drafting notes:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{[An \textasciigrave{}audience\textasciigrave{} attribute addresses a specific audience]\{.draftnote audience="the reader"\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Drafting note for the reader: An
\VERB|\NormalTok{audience}| attribute addresses a specific
audience {]}}}
\end{quote}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: draftnote}
\NormalTok{We don’t think we have to change anything here, since if \textasciigrave{}E\textasciigrave{} is a *splice{-}specifier*}
\NormalTok{that can be interpreted as a *splice{-}expression*, the requirements already fall out}
\NormalTok{based on how paragraphs 1 and 3 are already worded}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Drafting note: We don't think we have to change
anything here, since if \VERB|\NormalTok{E}| is a
\emph{splice-specifier} that can be interpreted as a
\emph{splice-expression}, the requirements already fall out based on how
paragraphs 1 and 3 are already worded {]}}
\end{quote}

To specify an audience for the
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{fenced
\VERB|\NormalTok{Div}| block}, you'll need
\VERB|\OperatorTok{:::} \OperatorTok{\{.}\NormalTok{draftnote audience}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"the reader"}\OperatorTok{\}}|.

Finally, in the relatively common situation where an example appears
within a note, you can simply nest them:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{::: note}
\NormalTok{The declaration of a class name takes effect immediately after the *identifier*}
\NormalTok{is seen in the class definition or *elaborated{-}type{-}specifier*.}

\NormalTok{::: example}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{class A * A;}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{first specifies \textasciigrave{}A\textasciigrave{} to be the name of a class and then redefines it as the name of}
\NormalTok{a pointer to an object of that class. This means that the elaborated form \textasciigrave{}class A\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{must be used to refer to the class. Such artistry with names can be confusing and}
\NormalTok{is best avoided.}
\NormalTok{:::}
\NormalTok{:::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

{{[} \emph{Note:} }The declaration of a class name takes effect
immediately after the \emph{identifier} is seen in the class definition
or \emph{elaborated-type-specifier}.

{{[} \emph{Example:} }

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ A }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ A}\OperatorTok{;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

first specifies \VERB|\NormalTok{A}| to be the name of a class and then
redefines it as the name of a pointer to an object of that class. This
means that the elaborated form \VERB|\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ A}|
must be used to refer to the class. Such artistry with names can be
confusing and is best avoided.{ --- \emph{end example} {]}}

{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Grammar\hyperref[grammar]{}}{Grammar}}\label{grammar}

Use \href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#line-blocks}{line blocks}
(\VERB|\OperatorTok{\VerbBar{}}|) in order to preserve the leading
spaces.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} | \_selection{-}statement:\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \textasciigrave{}if constexpr\textasciigrave{}\_\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \textasciigrave{}(\textasciigrave{} \_init{-}statement\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \_condition\_ \textasciigrave{})\textasciigrave{} \_statement\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \textasciigrave{}if constexpr\textasciigrave{}\_\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \textasciigrave{}(\textasciigrave{} \_init{-}statement\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \_condition\_ \textasciigrave{})\textasciigrave{} \_statement\_ \textasciigrave{}else\textasciigrave{} \_statement\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \textasciigrave{}switch (\textasciigrave{} \_init{-}statement\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \_condition\_ \textasciigrave{})\textasciigrave{} \_statement\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     [\textasciigrave{}inspect\textasciigrave{} \textasciigrave{}constexpr\textasciigrave{}\textasciitilde{}\_opt\_\textasciitilde{} \textasciigrave{}(\textasciigrave{} \_init{-}statement\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \_condition\_ \textasciigrave{})\textasciigrave{} \textasciigrave{}\{\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}            \_inspect{-}case{-}seq\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}        \textasciigrave{}\}\textasciigrave{}]\{.add\}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} ::: add}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} | \_inspect{-}case{-}seq:\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_inspect{-}case\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_inspect{-}case{-}seq\_ \_inspect{-}case\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} | \_inspect{-}case:\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_attribute{-}specifier{-}seq\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \_inspect{-}pattern\_ \_inspect{-}guard\textasciitilde{}opt\textasciitilde{}\_ \textasciigrave{}:\textasciigrave{} \_statement\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} | \_inspect{-}pattern:\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_wildcard{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_identifier{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_constant{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_structured{-}binding{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_alternative{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_binding{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \_extractor{-}pattern\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} | \_inspect{-}guard:\_}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} |     \textasciigrave{}if (\textasciigrave{} \_expression\_ \textasciigrave{})\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} :::}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\begin{quote}
\emph{selection-statement:}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{if} \KeywordTok{constexpr}|\emph{\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{if} \KeywordTok{constexpr}|\emph{\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}
\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{else}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{switch} \OperatorTok{(}|
\emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}} \emph{condition}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{inspect}|
\VERB|\NormalTok{constexpr}|\textsubscript{\emph{opt}}
\VERB|\NormalTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\NormalTok{)}| \VERB|\NormalTok{\{}|
\emph{inspect-case-seq} \VERB|\NormalTok{\}}|}}}

{\color[HTML]{006e28}

\emph{inspect-case-seq:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{inspect-case}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{inspect-case-seq} \emph{inspect-case}

\emph{inspect-case:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{attribute-specifier-seq\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{inspect-pattern} \emph{inspect-guard\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\NormalTok{:}| \emph{statement}

\emph{inspect-pattern:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{wildcard-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{identifier-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{constant-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{structured-binding-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{alternative-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{binding-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{extractor-pattern}

\emph{inspect-guard:}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\NormalTok{if (}| \emph{expression}
\VERB|\NormalTok{)}|

}
\end{quote}
\end{quote}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Code\hyperref[code]{}}{Code}}\label{code}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Inline
Code\hyperref[inline-code]{}}{Inline Code}}\label{inline-code}

Use backticks like
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}}| for
inline code.

We can use the Pandoc extension
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-inline_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{inline\_code\_attributes}|}
to specify which language should be used for syntax highlighting:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5524}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4476}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}auto value = std::format("\{\}", bar);\textasciigrave{}\{.cpp\}}|
&
\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ value }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ std}\OperatorTok{::}\NormalTok{format}\OperatorTok{(}\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\{\}}\StringTok{"}\OperatorTok{,}\NormalTok{ bar}\OperatorTok{);}| \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}let value = format!("\{bar\}");\textasciigrave{}\{.rust\}}|
&
\VERB|\KeywordTok{let}\NormalTok{ value }\OperatorTok{=} \PreprocessorTok{format!}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"\{bar\}"}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{;}| \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}value = f"\{bar\}"\textasciigrave{}\{.python\}}|
&
\VERB|\NormalTok{value }\OperatorTok{=} \SpecialStringTok{f"}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{bar}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{"}| \\
\end{longtable}
}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }\textbf{Inline Code gets C++ syntax highlighting by
default.}{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

Since we're writing a C++ proposal, many, if not most of the inline code
will be C++. Adding the \VERB|\NormalTok{\{.cpp\}}| attribute everywhere
can become very verbose, very fast. Thus, inline code is implicitly
interpreted as \VERB|\NormalTok{\{.cpp\}}|. For example,
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}}| is
implicitly
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}\{.cpp\}}|.

For no-syntax-highlighting, use \VERB|\NormalTok{\{.default\}}| like
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}\{.default\}}|.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5679}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4321}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}constexpr int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}}|
&
\VERB|\KeywordTok{constexpr} \DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{0}\OperatorTok{;}| \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}constexpr int x = 0;\textasciigrave{}\{.default\}}|
& \VERB|\NormalTok{constexpr int x = 0;}| \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Code
Block\hyperref[code-block]{}}{Code Block}}\label{code-block}

Use three or more backticks to start a code block.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3194}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.2500}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\NormalTok{int main() \{}
\NormalTok{  return 0;}
\NormalTok{\}}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{int main() \{}
\NormalTok{  return 0;}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{int main() \{}
\NormalTok{  return 0;}
\NormalTok{\}}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ main}\OperatorTok{()} \OperatorTok{\{}
  \ControlFlowTok{return} \DecValTok{0}\OperatorTok{;}
\OperatorTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }Unlike \hyperref[inline-code]{Inline Code}, code
blocks are not implicitly C++.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{numberLines}| class to a code
block to number the lines, and the
\VERB|\NormalTok{startFrom}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{N}| attribute to
specify the starting number, using the Pandoc extension:
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-fenced_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{fenced\_code\_attributes}|}.

