}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Embedded
Markdown\hyperref[embedded-markdown]{}}{Embedded Markdown}}\label{embedded-markdown}

Code in C++ proposals often needs small pieces of wording markup inside
it. With embedded Markdown enabled, text surrounded by
\VERB|\NormalTok{@}| is parsed as Markdown and then placed back into the
code element. This is useful for italicized terms, exposition-only
names, \hyperref[modifying-text]{modifying text}, and
\hyperref[stable-names]{stable names}.

Embedded Markdown is \textbf{enabled by default} for C++ and
no-syntax-highlighting code. This is essentially:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Inline code such as
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}code\textasciigrave{}}|,
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}code\textasciigrave{}\{.cpp\}}|,
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}code\textasciigrave{}\{.default\}}|,
  and
\item
  Code blocks that start with either
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}|,
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}|,
  or
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}default}|
\end{itemize}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Recall the \textasciigrave{}static\_cast\textasciigrave{} syntax: \textasciigrave{}static\_cast \textless{} @*type{-}id*@ \textgreater{} ( @*expression*@ )\textasciigrave{}.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

Recall the \VERB|\KeywordTok{static\_cast}| syntax:
\VERB|\KeywordTok{static\_cast} \OperatorTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{ \emph{type-id} }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{ \emph{expression} }\OperatorTok{)}|.
\end{quote}

Because italicized wording terms are so common,
\VERB|\NormalTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{\$}}}text{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{\$}}}}|
is provided as a shorthand for
\VERB|\NormalTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{@*}}}text{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{*@}}}}|.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Recall the \textasciigrave{}static\_cast\textasciigrave{} syntax: \textasciigrave{}static\_cast \textless{} $type{-}id$ \textgreater{} ( $expression$ )\textasciigrave{}.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

Recall the \VERB|\KeywordTok{static\_cast}| syntax:
\VERB|\KeywordTok{static\_cast} \OperatorTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{ \emph{type-id} }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{ \emph{expression} }\OperatorTok{)}|.
\end{quote}

A more elaborate example with \hyperref[modifying-text]{modifying text}:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{template \textless{}@[invocable](class)\{.sub\}@ F@[, class]\{.add\}@\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{struct $as{-}receiver$ \{}
\NormalTok{@[private:]\{.rm\}@}
\NormalTok{  @[using invocable\_type = std::remove\_cvref\_t\textless{}F\textgreater{};]\{.rm\}@}
\NormalTok{  @[invocable\_type](F)\{.sub\}@ f\_;}
\NormalTok{@[public:]\{.rm\}@}
\NormalTok{  @[explicit *as{-}receiver*(invocable\_type\&\& f)]\{.rm\}@}
\NormalTok{  @[*as{-}receiver*(*as{-}receiver*\&\& other) = default;]\{.rm\}@}
\NormalTok{  void set\_value() @[noexcept(is\_nothrow\_invocable\_v\textless{}F\&\textgreater{})]\{.add\}@ \{}
\NormalTok{    invoke(f\_);}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{  @[[[noreturn]]]\{.add\}@ void set\_error(std::exception\_ptr) @[noexcept]\{.add\}@ \{}
\NormalTok{    terminate();}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{  void set\_done() noexcept \{\}}
\NormalTok{\};}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{template} \OperatorTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{invocable}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{class}}}} F{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{, class}}}}\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}}
\KeywordTok{struct}\NormalTok{ \emph{as-receiver} }\OperatorTok{\{}
\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{private:}}}}
\NormalTok{  {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{using invocable\_type = std::remove\_cvref\_t\textless{}F\textgreater;}}}}
\NormalTok{  {{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{invocable\_type}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{F}}}} f\_}\OperatorTok{;}
\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{public:}}}}
\NormalTok{  {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{explicit \emph{as-receiver}(invocable\_type\&\& f)}}}}
\NormalTok{  {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{\emph{as-receiver}(\emph{as-receiver}\&\& other) = default;}}}}
  \DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ set\_value}\OperatorTok{()}\NormalTok{ {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{noexcept(is\_nothrow\_invocable\_v\textless{}F\&\textgreater)}}} }\OperatorTok{\{}
\NormalTok{    invoke}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{f\_}\OperatorTok{);}
  \OperatorTok{\}}
\NormalTok{  {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{{[}{[}noreturn{]}{]}}}} }\DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ set\_error}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{std}\OperatorTok{::}\NormalTok{exception\_ptr}\OperatorTok{)}\NormalTok{ {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{noexcept}}} }\OperatorTok{\{}
\NormalTok{    terminate}\OperatorTok{();}
  \OperatorTok{\}}
  \DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ set\_done}\OperatorTok{()} \KeywordTok{noexcept} \OperatorTok{\{\}}
\OperatorTok{\};}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{quote}

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{Code within Embedded
Markdown\hyperref[code-within-embedded-markdown]{}}{Code within Embedded Markdown}}\label{code-within-embedded-markdown}

Suppose we want to \textbf{add} a parameter
\VERB|\DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ i}| to a function
\VERB|\NormalTok{f}|:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3750}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3750}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{void f(@[int i]\{.add\}@);}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{int i}}}}\OperatorTok{);}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

This is perfectly fine, and quite intuitive. However, consider if the
parameter is something more complicated, like
\VERB|\NormalTok{\emph{foo} }\OperatorTok{*}\KeywordTok{const} \OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ptr}|:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{void f(@[*foo* *const *ptr]\{.add\}@);}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{foo} \emph{const }ptr}}}}\OperatorTok{);}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

Now, the pointers have disappeared and \VERB|\KeywordTok{const}| is
italicized. This is because the \textbf{full text} within
\VERB|\NormalTok{@}| is treated as Markdown, which is exactly what we
want for \VERB|\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{foo}\OperatorTok{*}| for
example. It's just not want we want for the
\VERB|\OperatorTok{*}\KeywordTok{const} \OperatorTok{*}| part of it.

There are a couple of ways to resolve this issue:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  Introduce an \textbf{inline code within the embedded Markdown}:

  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{void f(@[\textasciigrave{}$foo$ *const *ptr\textasciigrave{}]\{.add\}@);}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

  \textbf{Rendered Output}

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{\emph{foo} *const *ptr}|}}}}\OperatorTok{);}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}
  \end{quote}

  Given that
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}$foo$ *const *ptr\textasciigrave{}}|
  is exactly how it would be written if we were writing inline code,
  this is a decent solution.

  However, this approach can't really handle markup more complicated
  than italicizing because the parsing of \VERB|\NormalTok{@}| is
  extremely naive in its current implementation.
\item
  \textbf{Escape the special Markdown characters} that you want
  interpreted literally. Any symbol can be escaped with a backslash like
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\textbackslash{}}\OperatorTok{*}|, and is interpreted
  literally by the Pandoc extension:
  \href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-all_symbols_escapable}{\VERB|\NormalTok{all\_symbols\_escapable}|}.

  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{void f(@[*foo* \textbackslash{}*const \textbackslash{}*ptr]\{.add\}@);}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

  \textbf{Rendered Output}

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{foo} *const *ptr}}}}\OperatorTok{);}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}
  \end{quote}

  This approach can handle more complicated markup requirements. For
  example, if \VERB|\NormalTok{foo}| needed to be bolded instead, we can
  just do:

  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{void f(@[**foo** \textbackslash{}*const \textbackslash{}*ptr]\{.add\}@);}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

  \textbf{Rendered Output}

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \DataTypeTok{void}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{(}\NormalTok{{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\textbf{foo} *const *ptr}}}}\OperatorTok{);}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{Opt-out for Default Languages:
\texttt{.raw}\hyperref[opt-out-for-default-languages-.raw]{}}{Opt-out for Default Languages: .raw}}\label{opt-out-for-default-languages-.raw}

Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{raw}| class to opt-out of
embedded Markdown, using Pandoc extensions
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-inline_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{inline\_code\_attributes}|}
or
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-fenced_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{fenced\_code\_attributes}|}.

One example of a problem involving emails:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp \{.raw\}}
\NormalTok{auto emails = \{ "a@mail.com", "b@mail.com" \};}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ emails }\OperatorTok{=} \OperatorTok{\{} \StringTok{"a@mail.com"}\OperatorTok{,} \StringTok{"b@mail.com"} \OperatorTok{\};}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}cpp}
\NormalTok{auto emails = \{ "a@mail.com", "b@mail.com" \};}
\NormalTok{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ emails }\OperatorTok{=} \OperatorTok{\{} \StringTok{"amail.com", "bmail.com"} \OperatorTok{\};}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

The \VERB|\NormalTok{@}| characters ``disappear'' without the
\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{raw}| class because the text between the
two \VERB|\NormalTok{@}|,
\VERB|\NormalTok{domain}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{com}\StringTok{", "}\NormalTok{bar}|
is parsed as Markdown, and placed back into the full range of
\VERB|\NormalTok{@domain.com", "bar@}|.

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{Opt-in for Other Languages:
\texttt{.embed\_md}\hyperref[embed_md]{}}{Opt-in for Other Languages: .embed\_md}}\label{embed_md}

Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{embed\_md}| class to opt-in for
embedded Markdown, using Pandoc extensions
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-inline_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{inline\_code\_attributes}|}
or
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-fenced_code_attributes}{\VERB|\NormalTok{fenced\_code\_attributes}|}.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5478}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4522}}@{}}
