\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Stable
Names\hyperref[stable-names]{}}{Stable Names}}\label{stable-names}

Stable names come in two flavors: \emph{explicit} and \emph{implicit} .

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }Run \VERB|\NormalTok{make update}| to re-fetch and
update the local databases, including stable
names.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Implicit Stable
Names\hyperref[implicit-stable-names]{}}{Implicit Stable Names}}\label{implicit-stable-names}

\emph{Implicit} stable names are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#extension-shortcut_reference_links}{\VERB|\NormalTok{shortcut\_reference\_links}|}
such as
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{stable}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{name}\OperatorTok{]}|.
It automatically links to \url{https://eel.is/c++draft/stable.name}, if
such a stable name exists. This is typically used in quoting standard
paragraphs like this:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\textgreater{} [...] whose lifetime has begun and has not ended ([basic.life]).}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

\begin{quote}
{[}\ldots{]} whose lifetime has begun and has not ended
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}).
\end{quote}
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Explicit Stable
Names\hyperref[explicit-stable-names]{}}{Explicit Stable Names}}\label{explicit-stable-names}

\emph{Explicit} stable names are
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#divs-and-spans}{bracketed
\VERB|\NormalTok{Span}| elements} that look like:
\VERB|\NormalTok{[stable.name]{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{\{.sref\}}}}}|.
By default, a leading section number and the section title is
automatically rendered.

For example:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Modify section [basic.life]\{.sref\}:}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Modify section {6.8.4 Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}}:
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

This is also useful in a header when updating large bodies of wording:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#\# [basic.life]\{.sref\} \{{-} .unlisted\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{{6.8.4 Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}}\hyperref[basic.life]{}}{6.8.4 Lifetime {[}basic.life{]}}}\label{basic.life}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }The \VERB|\NormalTok{\{{-} .unlisted\}}| is applied
to the header itself, to \hyperref[disable-section-number]{disable the
section numbering} and to \hyperref[exclude-from-toc]{exclude it from
the table of contents}{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

Lastly, you may also add the class \VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}| or
\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{unnumbered}| to to omit the section
number.

This is useful if you prefer to use the regular header numbering
instead:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{\#\# [basic.life]\{{-} .sref\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{4.9 {Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}}\hyperref[basic-life-2]{}}{4.9 Lifetime {[}basic.life{]}}}\label{basic-life-2}
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

See
\hyperref[control-numbering]{Control the Numbering of Explicit Stable Names}
for how to disable numbering at the document-level.

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Paragraph
Link\hyperref[paragraph-link]{}}{Paragraph Link}}\label{paragraph-link}

A suffix \VERB|\NormalTok{/pnum}| can be added to link to a specific
paragraph number, where \VERB|\NormalTok{pnum}| is a dot-separated
integers like \VERB|\DecValTok{1}| or \VERB|\FloatTok{2.1}|.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Refer to a specific paragraph [basic.life]/1:}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Refer to a specific paragraph
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#1}{{[}basic.life{]}/1}:
\end{minipage} \\
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Change [basic.life]\{.sref\}/2.1 as follows:}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Change {6.8.4 Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#2.1}{{[}basic.life{]}/2.1}} as
follows:
\end{minipage} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Citations\hyperref[citations]{}}{Citations}}\label{citations}

In-text citations look like this: \VERB|\NormalTok{[@paper]}|

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{This is a proposal for a reduced initial set of features to support static}
\NormalTok{reflection in C++. Specifically we are mostly proposing a subset of features}
\NormalTok{suggested in [@P1240R2].}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

This is a proposal for a reduced initial set of features to support
static reflection in C++. Specifically we are mostly proposing a subset
of features suggested in
\href{https://wg21.link/p1240r2}{{[}P1240R2{]}}.
\end{quote}

You may also include the title of the paper by adding the
\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{title}| class, like
\VERB|\NormalTok{[@paper]{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{\{.title\}}}}}|
which generates:

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{This is a proposal for a reduced initial set of features to support static}
\NormalTok{reflection in C++. Specifically we are mostly proposing a subset of features}
\NormalTok{suggested in [@P1240R2]\{.title\}.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

This is a proposal for a reduced initial set of features to support
static reflection in C++. Specifically we are mostly proposing a subset
of features suggested in {\href{https://wg21.link/p1240r2}{{[}P1240R2{]}
(Scalable Reflection)}}.
\end{quote}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{References\hyperref[references]{}}{References}}\label{references}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Automatic
References\hyperref[automatic-references]{}}{Automatic References}}\label{automatic-references}

The bibliography is automatically generated from
\url{https://wg21.link/index.yaml} for citations of the following types.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.2920}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.7080}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Type}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Identifier}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Paper & \textbf{N}\emph{xxxx} /
\textbf{P}\emph{xxxx}\textbf{R}\emph{n} \\
Issue & \textbf{CWG}\emph{xxxx} / \textbf{EWG}\emph{xxxx} /
\textbf{LWG}\emph{xxxx} / \textbf{LEWG}\emph{xxxx} /
\textbf{FS}\emph{xxxx} \\
Editorial & \textbf{EDIT}\emph{xxx} \\
Standing Document & \textbf{SD}\emph{x} \\
\end{longtable}
}

The \VERB|\NormalTok{[@P1240R2]}| example from
\hyperref[citations]{Citations} produces a bibliography entry:
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{P1240R2}\OperatorTok{]}| in
\hyperref[bibliography]{References}.

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }Run \VERB|\NormalTok{make update}| to re-fetch and
update the local databases, including the automatic
references.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Manual
References\hyperref[manual-references]{}}{Manual References}}\label{manual-references}

Manual references are specified in a YAML metadata block similar to
\hyperref[title]{Title}, typically at the bottom of the document.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Markdown Source}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{The \textasciigrave{}id\textasciigrave{} field is for in{-}text citations (e.g., [@PAT]),}
\NormalTok{and \textasciigrave{}citation{-}label\textasciigrave{} is the label for the reference.}

\NormalTok{Typically \textasciigrave{}id\textasciigrave{} and \textasciigrave{}citation{-}label\textasciigrave{} are kept the same.}

\NormalTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\NormalTok{references:}
\NormalTok{  {-} id: PAT}
\NormalTok{    citation{-}label: Patterns}
\NormalTok{    title: "Pattern Matching in C++"}
\NormalTok{    author:}
\NormalTok{      {-} family: Park}
\NormalTok{        given: Michael}
\NormalTok{    URL: https://github.com/mpark/patterns}
\NormalTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Rendered Output}

The \VERB|\NormalTok{id}| field is for in-text citations (e.g.,
\href{https://github.com/mpark/patterns}{{[}Patterns{]}}), and
\VERB|\NormalTok{citation}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{label}| is the
label for the reference.

Typically \VERB|\NormalTok{id}| and
\VERB|\NormalTok{citation}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{label}| are kept
the same.
\end{quote}

This produces a bibliography entry
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{Patterns}\OperatorTok{]}| in
\hyperref[bibliography]{References}.

\section{\texorpdfstring{Configurations\hyperref[configurations]{}}{Configurations}}\label{configurations}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Default Language for Code
Elements\hyperref[default-language-for-code-elements]{}}{Default Language for Code Elements}}\label{default-language-for-code-elements}

As mentioned in sections \hyperref[inline-code]{Inline Code} and
\hyperref[code-block]{Code Block}, inline code elements are C++ syntax
highlighted by default, while code blocks are not.

The default configuration is:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{highlighting}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }
\AttributeTok{  }\FunctionTok{inline{-}code}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ cpp}
\AttributeTok{  }\FunctionTok{code{-}block}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ default}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You could change this for your document by adding both or either entries
to the YAML metadata block. For example, if you also want code blocks to
be C++ by default:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{highlighting:}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{code-block: cpp}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

or if you want inline-code to be treated normally, not as C++:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{highlighting:}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{inline-code: default}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Embedded Markdown by Default Code
Classes\hyperref[embedded-markdown-by-default-code-classes]{}}{Embedded Markdown by Default Code Classes}}\label{embedded-markdown-by-default-code-classes}

\hyperref[embedded-markdown]{Embedded Markdown} is enabled by default
for \VERB|\NormalTok{cpp}| and \VERB|\NormalTok{default}| code elements.

While the
\hyperref[embed_md]{\VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{embed\_md}|} class
should be suffcient for most use cases to enable embedded Markdown as
needed, if you want to change the default, you can set the
\VERB|\NormalTok{embedded}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{md}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{code}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{classes}|
YAML metadata. For example:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{embedded-md-code-classes:}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{- cpp}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{- default}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{- diff}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{- nasm}}}}
\AttributeTok{  {{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{- rust}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This is an \textbf{override} for the existing list of
\VERB|\NormalTok{cpp}| and \VERB|\NormalTok{default}|, so if it's
desired to keep \VERB|\NormalTok{cpp}| and \VERB|\NormalTok{default}| to
have embedded Markdown enabled by default, they must be listed again.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Control the Numbering of Explicit Stable
Names\hyperref[control-numbering]{}}{Control the Numbering of Explicit Stable Names}}\label{control-numbering}

By default \emph{explicit} stable names such as
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{.sref\}}| renders with a leading section
number and the section title.

As mentioned in \hyperref[explicit-stable-names]{Explicit Stable Names},
you can disable numbering at the element-level via
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{basic}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{life}\OperatorTok{]\{{-}} \OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{sref}\OperatorTok{\}}|
or
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{basic}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{life}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{unnumbered }\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{sref}\OperatorTok{\}}|.
To disable at the document-level, you can specify
\VERB|\NormalTok{number}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{srefs}\OperatorTok{:} \KeywordTok{false}|
in the YAML metadata:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{number-srefs: false}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Unicode
Fonts\hyperref[unicode-fonts]{}}{Unicode Fonts}}\label{unicode-fonts}

If building for PDF (via LaTeX) output with Unicode characters, you may
want to select specific
\href{https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html\#fonts}{Fonts} for rendering. For
example, \VERB|\NormalTok{monofont}| can be specified in the YAML
metadata block to select a font for code elements.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"\textasciigrave{}MPark/WG21\textasciigrave{} User\textquotesingle{}s Guide"}
\FunctionTok{subtitle}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Framework for Writing C++ Committee Proposals"}
\FunctionTok{document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ D0000R0}
\FunctionTok{date}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ today}
\FunctionTok{audience}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ WG21}
\FunctionTok{author}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\KeywordTok{{-}}\AttributeTok{ }\FunctionTok{name}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ Michael Park}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{email}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ \textless{}mcypark@gmail.com\textgreater{}}
\AttributeTok{{{\setlength{\fboxsep}{1pt}\colorbox{yellow}{monofont: "DejaVu Sans Mono"}}}}
\PreprocessorTok{{-}{-}{-}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

``DejaVu Sans Mono'' provides glyphs for a large amount of the Unicode
characters. If you want the list of available fonts on your system, most
supported systems will produce a list via the command-line tool
\VERB|\NormalTok{fc}\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{list}|.

